How easy lines were to follow

Visual aspects that impacted my choice included legibility and visibility - by which I mean ease of seeing the different connections. This often correlated to larger diagrams, as they had more space and were easier visually to decipher. (I'm not sure if this is using the term correctly, but it seemed less "stressful" to me to do so.) These drawings with more space between lines and circles were easier and more pleasant for me to interact with, so I generally chose those.

1. I prefer a drawing with larger distances between nodes. 
2. I prefer a drawing with arcs separated with each other.

Overall shape - preference for a larger, more rounded shape.

Distance between dots - preference for greater distance
Number of connections coming off each dot - preference for fewer.
My choice was base on clear diagram, once I could I identify their traces.
line style and thickness.

I found myself preferring the pattern that looks more multidimensional. Multidimensional scaling appears more structured and provides more information about the connections between the nodes and the distances among them.
I chose drawings that were more organised, had more space between links or had distinctive patterns.
System Integration Diagrams: Illustrate interactions between systems and components.
The visual aspect of drawing that affected my choice where the plain drawings ,loved the unique ones, the diagrams and links been twisted in between was cool.

Clutter of the diagram and the ambiguity of lines that overlapped were key determinants as to whether a diagram was preferred. Some diagrams were confusing as the lines crossed other lines too much or followed similar pathways.

I preferred the ones that somewhat resembled actual objects. If neither looked like actual objects, I would pick the one that was easiest to read as a map, like the friendship group example shown at the beginning of the study
The distance kept and the tidiness of the drawings
how neat the shape and the design is
I disliked overlapping edges, and preferred evenly spaced nodes.
I think I preferred shorter lines, and wider spaces (between lines).
The easiness to connect the relationship
The more spaces in-between the better I liked the diagram. I felt that they were easier to read

where the lines were very close together, it was hard to see the connections and looked cluttered and stressful. I prefer bigger spaces.
I don't like a lot of dense lines backed into a small space.
The drawings that had a lot of connections, that were a bit closer to each other.

I prefer the dots not too close to each other, so that the diagrams are clearer and the lines are more distinctive. I also like each part of the diagram to be of similar size, not like a massive area on one side and then several smaller areas with many lines and dots on the other side.
I preferred the more simple diagrams, the ones with less overlapping lines, and clearer points.
I prefered the networks that had the nodes as spread out as possible. I felt these were easier to take in all the interlinked possibilities. Networks that looked messy or chaotic were unappealing.
I had a preference for when there were minimal lines overlapping. I prefered when the image was not cluttered.
I preferred the visuals that had more of the simple line drawings so that are easier to understand and see.
